### Based on Nature of Eruption and Surface Form

1. **Shield Volcanoes**: `Dome-shaped` volcanoes formed by lava slowly oozing out. They can reach heights of up to `9000` meters.
   *Example:* [Hawaiian volcanoes](https://media-cldnry.s-nbcnews.com/image/upload/t_nbcnews-fp-1024-512,f_auto,q_auto:best/rockcms/2025-08/volcano1-c152d0.jpg)

2. **Strato (Composite) Volcanoes**: Made of multiple layers of `hardened` lava, tephra, pumice, and volcanic ash, forming a cone shape. Heights vary from `100 to 3500` meters.
   *Example:* [Mount Etna](https://www.go-etna.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/mount_etna-600x450.jpg)

3. **Cinder Cone Volcanoes**: Small cone-shaped mountains formed from `cooled magma` (cinders). Heights usually range from `100 to 400` meters.
   *Example:* [Krakatoa](https://images.theconversation.com/files/362457/original/file-20201008-22-5bqu3h.jpg?ixlib=rb-4.1.0&amp;rect=0%2C344%2C5463%2C3293&amp;q=20&amp;auto=format&amp;w=320&amp;fit=clip&amp;dpr=2&amp;usm=12&amp;cs=strip)

4. **Mid-Oceanic Ridge Volcanoes**: Found in oceanic areas, especially along mid-ocean ridges. These volcanoes experience frequent eruptions at their central portions. [see example](https://images.theconversation.com/files/566709/original/file-20231219-15-ok6pkd.jpg?ixlib=rb-4.1.0&amp;rect=23%2C0%2C3962%2C2659&amp;q=45&amp;auto=format&amp;w=496&amp;fit=clip)
